You can solve this with a custom [`TypeAdapterFactory`](https://javadoc.io/doc/com.google.code.gson/gson/latest/com.google.gson/com/google/gson/TypeAdapterFactory.html) and a [`@JsonAdapter`](https://javadoc.io/doc/com.google.code.gson/gson/latest/com.google.gson/com/google/gson/annotations/JsonAdapter.html) annotation on the fields whose value might be wrapped.

The `TypeAdapterFactory` is used to get the delegate adapter (for example `List&lt;Contact&gt;`) and then creates an adapter which unwraps the JSON, if necessary. The `@JsonAdapter` annotation is used to apply this factory only to the affected fields, and not in general to all `List` values.

```java
/**
 * Gson {@link TypeAdapterFactory} which unwraps lists inside JSON objects, if
 * necessary.
 * 
 * &lt;p&gt;Must &lt;b&gt;only&lt;/b&gt; be used with {@link JsonAdapter @JsonAdapter}.
 */
public static class WrappedListTypeAdapterFactory implements TypeAdapterFactory {
    // Default constructor to allow Gson to create instances
    public WrappedListTypeAdapterFactory() { }

    @Override
    public &lt;T&gt; TypeAdapter&lt;T&gt; create(Gson gson, TypeToken&lt;T&gt; type) {
        // Get the actual adapter, for example for `List&lt;Contact&gt;`
        // Note: Cannot use Gson.getDelegateAdapter, see https://github.com/google/gson/issues/1028
        TypeAdapter&lt;T&gt; delegate = gson.getAdapter(type);

        return new TypeAdapter&lt;T&gt;() {
            @Override
            public void write(JsonWriter out, T value) throws IOException {
                delegate.write(out, value);
            }

            @Override
